						               													<description>Dioses del Nilo is a strategic and tactical board game for two players based on Egyptian mythology. The objective of each player is to defeat their opponent by skillfully moving their pieces on the board.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;How to play?&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The game is divided into two phases: the placement phase and the combat phase.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player's field is divided into two: vanguard and rearguard.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Each player must make a movement in each phase in an orderly manner and alternate with the opponent.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Placement phase:&amp;#10;In this phase the players both take 2 tiles from their tile column (the bottom two tiles). Then in turn (starting with the one with the clock on their side of the field) Place a token inside the field on any space you want.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Tokens that are placed in the rear can be placed face down.&amp;#10;Tiles placed in the vangauard are always placed face up.&amp;#10;Once a player places a token, he passes the other player's turn by sliding the clock card to the other player's side.&amp;#10;Once all the players have placed their 2 tokens, we proceed to the combat phase.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Combat phase:&amp;#10;Starting with the player who has the clock on his side of the field, he can make one of the following moves:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Move a soldier to an adjacent square (left or right, up or down) The soldier cannot be moved diagonally.&amp;#10;Attack an enemy square.&amp;#10;End the turn.&amp;#10;Once a player has made a move, it automatically passes to the other player and the clock moves to their side of the field.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Attacking and Defending&amp;#10;When a soldier attacks an enemy square, if there is an enemy soldier on that square, then both fight. The higher number wins.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The losing token &amp;quot;perishes&amp;quot; and is placed on top of its face-up god card [Graveyard]. Tokens that have perished in battle can be consulted by the opponent at any time. If there is a tie, both pieces perish.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The winning soldier must recharge energy, so he places himself at the top of the face-up token column, waiting for his turn to return to action.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the designer&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
